851.title: Prereq (archive)
headers: The restriction operator of any characteristic operator to the generalized eigenspace corresponding to a different eigenvalue is injective

The characteristic polynomial of the restriction operator of any linear operator on a finite-dimensional vector space with splitting characteristic polynomial to a generalized eigenspace is a monomial shifted by the eigenvalue

Dimension of generalized eigenspace in a finite-dimensional vector space corresponding to any eigenvalue of a linear operator with splitting characteristic polynomial is bounded by its algebraic multiplicity

Generalized eigenspace corresponding to any eigenvalue of a linear operator on a finite-dimensional vector space with splitting characteristic polynomial is the kernel of its characteristic operator iterated algebraic multiplicity times
Every finite-dimensional vector space is the sum of all generalized eigenspaces of a linear operator with splitting characteristic polynomial
The union of bases for generalized eigenspaces of a linear operator with splitting characteristic polynomial is disjoint
The disjoint union of bases for generalized eigenspaces of a linear operator with splitting characteristic polynomial is a basis for the domain

Dimension of generalized eigenspace in a finite-dimensional vector space corresponding to any eigenvalue of a linear operator with splitting characteristic polynomial is equal to its algebraic multiplicity
A linear operator on a finite-dimensional vector space with a splitting characteristic polynomial is diagonalizable iff each eigenspace is equal to the generalized eigenspace
Every finite-dimensional vector space is a direct sum of generalized eigenspaces of a linear operator with splitting characteristic polynomial
Span of any Jordan chain is an invariant subspace
The matrix representation of the restriction operator to the span of any Jordan chain with respect itself is a Jordan block
The disjoint union of Jordan chains that constitudes for a basis for a finite-dimensional vector space is a Jordan canonical basis
The Jordan chains corresponding to any eigenvalue with distinct initial vectors is disjoint
The finite disjoint union of Jordan chains corresponding to any eigenvalue with linearly independent initial vectors is linearly independent
Every generalized eigenspace in a finite-dimensional vector space has a basis consisting of a union of disjoint Jordan chains
Every linear operator on a finite-dimensional vector space with splitting characteristic polynomial has a Jordan canonical form
